ikipedia.org/wiki/Pierre-Simon_Laplace" title=3D"Pierre-Simon Laplace">Pier=
re-Simon Laplace</a> had been familiar with it before Gram and Schmidt.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Gram%E2%80%93Schmidt_process#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In the theory of =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lie_group_decompositions" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Lie group decompositions">Lie group decompositions</=
a>, it is generalized by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iwasa=
wa_decomposition" title=3D"Iwasawa decomposition">Iwasawa decomposition</a>=
.
</p><p>The application of the Gram=E2=80=93Schmidt process to the column ve=
ctors of a full column <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rank_(linea=
r_algebra)" title=3D"Rank (linear algebra)">rank</a> <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_(mathematics)" title=3D"Matrix (mathematics)">mat=
rix</a> yields the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/QR_decompositio=
n" title=3D"QR decomposition">QR decomposition</a> (it is decomposed into a=
n <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthogonal_matrix" title=3D"Orth=
ogonal matrix">orthogonal</a> and a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Triangular_matrix" title=3D"Triangular matrix">triangular matrix</a>).
</p>
